At its core, this project is designed to understand  and, therefore, replicate  how a 9x9 Sudoku board works. Each of the 81 cells must contain a digit from 1-9. However, it follows a strict rule in which every single column, row, and individual 3x3 boxes must have a distinct value without any repetitions/duplicates. Through this project, we initially introduce an empty grid where all 81 cells are filled with the value 0 to denote that it is empty. However, we must later (partially) fill  some of the cells before we start to solve the rest of the puzzle. This step truly depends on game design and whether the program is meant to only generate a complete Sudoku puzzle or allow users to interact with the puzzle. For instance, if  one is simply creating a generator, it would be easier to fill in an entire row or column, however, if users' experience is prioritized then the program would need to fill in at least 30 cells. Overall, the objective of this project is to use recursive  methods to print out a solved Sudoku puzzle. 
My data structure  includes 2D arrays and ArrayLists. However, it builds off a private instance variable called board, which holds the 9x9 dimension we need to build our Sudoku. Using a 2D array was efficient because it allowed me to access specific rows and columns very quickly. This is also evident by the fact that the time complexity to access indexes for 2D arrays is O(1). Later, I opted to use an ArrayList to introduce a row of known values in my grid. I initially wanted to use a 1D array, with int[]  numBank = {1,2,3,4,5,6,7,8,9}, since it was easier to automatically set the values within the array. I wanted to use this bank of numbers to add a distinct value to the first row of the board. I wanted to remove the numbers from the  numBank directly after it was added to the board. This would ensure that the numbers do not repeat in the first row. However, I got stuck since you can’t directly change the size of a 1D array. Hence, I  used a for loop to add the numbers 1-9, inside of an ArrayList called numBank. This way I would easily access those digits and readily remove the digits from numBank once I was done using it. 
The program includes a total of 5 methods: initializeBoard(), checkPosition(), solvedBoard(),  print(), and main(String[] args). Each of these methods exists to serve a different role in order to generate a solved Sudoku board. As I mentioned above, I initialized a 2D array called board and used a constructor(SudokuGenerator()) to declare a 9x9 board, where every single grid was initialized to be 0. However, through the method InitializeBoard(), I introduced an ArrayList containing numbers from 1-9, and filled in the first row of the board. Each of the numbers were removed from ArrayList once they were used up by the board to ensure that there were no duplicates in the first row. In the second method,  checkPosition(),  I checked over the three conditions that any Sudoku board must follow. It takes in the parameters r, c and num to check whether num already exists in any existing column, row or in any 3x3 box. It contains a boolean called solvedStatus, which returns true if the board abides by all the three rules and false if otherwise. This method is what powers the most important method, which is solvedBoard(). This method checks every single cell to identify empty cells it must fill. Through a for loop, it tries to plug in every single digit(1-9) one by one to check which digit will actually work. This process is done by identifying the index’s respective row and column. And then process these numbers through checkPositions(), which ensures the digit we are trying to plug in to our index doesn't exist elsewhere.  In the print() method, I used a for loop to print out all the respective rows and columns of the solved board. And,  I also printed out some borders and dividers. Lastly, in main(), I introduced an object called board that stores a new Sudoku puzzle. This board runs through all the previous methods mentioned above. And if it is solvable then it will print otherwise, it prints a failure message. 
As indicated by the previous paragraph, for the main part of my design I used a recursive algorithm to solve the Sudoku board.  The method solvedBoard() checks for empty cells it can fill. It calls upon itself until the whole board is filled. In which case the method returns true, meaning that the puzzle has been solved. 
In order to ensure that the program produced an accurate Sudoku board, I implemented multiple for loops. For example, initializeBoard() uses a for loop to ensure that the first row only has a unique value from 1-9, with no replication. Our method ensures that even with randomization, our board does not break the fundamental rule of a Sudoku board: which is that each row must have a distinct number. And, also, in checkPosition(), I ensured that if we added a value to an index then it would not appear in any of the respective columns, rows or 3x3 grid. Through these testing methods, I was able to print out a solved Sudoku board.
